  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT312-kilavi">iravukkuṟi vantu nīṅkukiṉṟa talaimakaṉ taṉṉeñciṟku varaivuṭaimai vēṭpak
          kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken, while [he?] wanted the possession of marriage,
          to his heart, by HIM, who leaves [her] after having come to the night tryst. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT312">
          <l> iraṇṭaṟi kaḷvinaṅ kāta lōḷē</l>
          <l> muraṇko ṭuppiṟ cevvēṉ malaiyaṉ</l>
          <l> muḷḷūrk kāṉa nāṟa vantu</l>
          <l> naḷḷeṉ kaṅku ṉammō raṉṉaḷ</l>
          <l> kūntal vēynta viravumala rutirttuc</l>
          <l> cāntuḷar naṟuṅkatup peṇṇey nīvi</l>
          <l> yamarā mukatta ḷākit</l>
          <l> tamarō raṉṉaḷ vaikaṟai yāṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>A double-faced robberess <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> kaḷvi </term> as the feminine counterpart of <term xml:lang="ta"> kaḷvaṉ </term> is attested only here in the old anthologies.    </note> our love!</l>
          <l>As if she [were] just ours in soundless night,</l>
          <l rend="indent">come to be fragrant in the forest on the Muḷḷūr mountain</l>
          <l rend="indent2">of Malaiyaṉ with red spear [and] the vigour</l>
          <l rend="indent7">to take on [any] antagonism,</l>
          <l>but <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> vaikaṟaiyāṉē </term> gains emphasis by the case suffix and the end position.   </note> at dawn as if she [were] just theirs,</l>
          <l>one with a settled face, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> amarā </term> is to be understood either as a positive <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam </term> in <term xml:lang="ta"> -ā </term>, or, in case this should be the more usual negative <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam </term> in <term xml:lang="ta">-ā </term>, then derived from the transitive <term xml:lang="ta"> amar </term> "to wish" = "without wish". T.V.G. reads it as a negative, giving the meaning a "face not suitable [to betray our intimacy]".   </note></l>
          <l rend="indent2">thrown off mixed blossoms that decked [her] tresses,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">sesame oil applied to the fragrant hair, smoothed</l>
          <l rend="indent9">with sandal paste.</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="2b">
            <l>of Malaiyaṉ with a resilient spear red as coral, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> tuppu </term> is a multivalent word the basic meaning of which, as far as the old anthologies are concerned, seems to be something like "fighting spirit, vigour". One of the further meanings, however, is a sort of red substance, often translated as "coral" (for a discussion of some material related to this strand see Tieken 1996: 422f.). Of almost two dozen occurrences in the KT, NA, AN and PN, the only other clear instance of "red colour" is AN 9.8 ( <term xml:lang="ta">tuppiṉ aṉṉa cem kōṭṭu iyaviṉ </term> "on the way through peaks red as <term xml:lang="ta"> tuppu </term>"). For this KT passage both meanings seem to make sense.</note></l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
